song_theme, result dbl (1): order ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data. ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message. ``` ::: ::: Abram made use of the slightly exotic `%<>%` pipe, which passes its output back to its first argument. Some data tidying and basic exploration: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} songs %<>% mutate(artist = if_else(artist == "*NSYNC", "NSYNC", artist)) songs_n <- songs %>% group_by(artist, song) %>% summarise(n = n()) %>% arrange(-n) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` `summarise()` has grouped output by 'artist'. You can override using the `.groups` argument. ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} artists_n <- songs %>% group_by(artist) %>% summarise(n = n()) %>% arrange(-n) winning_songs <- songs %>% group_by(artist, song, result) %>% summarise(n = n()) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` `summarise()` has grouped output by 'artist', 'song'. You can override using the `.groups` argument. ``` ::: ::: ## Exploration First we looked at viewing figures by show number and by season ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ratings %>% filter(!is.na(viewers_in_millions)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = show_number, y = viewers_in_millions)) + geom_point() + geom_line() + facet_wrap(vars(season), scales = "free_y") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-4-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: Then some preparation of the date column to get it in date format: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ratings %<>% mutate(airdate = if_else(season == 13, paste0(airdate, ", 2014"), airdate), proper_airdate = mdy(airdate)) ``` ::: Then a visualisation over time ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ratings %>% ggplot(aes(x = proper_airdate, y = viewers_in_millions)) + geom_point() + expand_limits(y = 0) + stat_smooth() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x' ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range (`stat_smooth()`). ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range (`geom_point()`). ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: Tabulation: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tabyl(ratings$season) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` ratings$season n percent 1 25 0.04215852 2 41 0.06913997 3 44 0.07419899 4 43 0.07251265 5 41 0.06913997 6 41 0.06913997 7 42 0.07082631 8 40 0.06745363 9 43 0.07251265 10 39 0.06576728 11 40 0.06745363 12 37 0.06239460 13 39 0.06576728 15 24 0.04047218 16 19 0.03204047 17 19 0.03204047 18 16 0.02698145 ``` ::: ::: Now average views ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} average_views <- ratings %>% group_by(season) %>% summarise(avg_views = mean(viewers_in_millions, na.rm = TRUE)) ``` ::: We saw a jump in most seasons at the very end, so decided to look at how big a proportional jump this was: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} rel_views <- ratings %>% group_by(season) %>% slice_tail(n=2) %>% summarise(relative_views = viewers_in_millions[2]/viewers_in_millions[1]) ``` ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} rel_views %>% ggplot(aes(x = season, y = relative_views)) + geom_point() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: Then average views ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} average_views %>% ggplot(aes(season, avg_views)) + geom_line() + expand_limits(y = 0) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: Now to join average views (over whole season) to with jump at the end (rel_views) to see if any obvious relationship: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} full_join(average_views, rel_views) %>% ggplot(aes(x = avg_views, y = relative_views)) + geom_point() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Joining with `by = join_by(season)` ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-12-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: Nope.. Another pattern we saw was that the first episode in a season seemed to be about the most popular, then there was a drop-off over time ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ratings %<>% group_by(season) %>% arrange(show_number) %>% mutate(share_of_first = viewers_in_millions / viewers_in_millions[1]) ratings %>% ggplot(aes(show_number, share_of_first, group = season, color = as.factor(season))) + geom_line() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-13-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: Finally, we looked at an interactive visualising using the `ggplotly()` convenience function using the `plotly` package: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} gg<- ratings %>% filter(season >= 3) %>% ggplot(aes(show_number, share_of_first, group = season, color = as.factor(season))) + geom_point() + scale_y_log10() ggplotly(gg) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
